{"title_page": "Edward Smith-Stanley, 12th Earl of Derby", "text_new": "{{Short description|British peer and politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name             = The Earl of Derby\n| honorific-suffix = [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]]\n| image            = Lord-derby.jpg\n| caption          =\n| order1           = [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n| term_start1      = 29 April 1783\n| term_end1        = 17 December 1783\n| monarch1         = [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]]\n| primeminister1   = [[William Cavendish-Bentinck, 3rd Duke of Portland|The Duke of Portland]]\n| predecessor1     = [[John Dunning, 1st Baron Ashburton|The Lord Ashburton]]\n| successor1       = [[Thomas Villiers, 1st Earl of Clarendon|The Earl of Clarendon]]\n| term_start2      = 12 February 1806\n| term_end2        = 31 March 1807\n| monarch2         = [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]]\n| primeminister2   = [[William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville|The Lord Grenville]]\n| predecessor2     = [[Dudley Ryder, 1st Earl of Harrowby|The Lord Harrowby]]\n| successor2       = [[Spencer Perceval|Hon. Spencer Perceval]]\n| birth_date       = 1 September 1752 ([[Old Style and New Style dates|O.S.]]) [12 September 1752 ([[Old Style and New Style dates|N.S.]])]\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       = 21 October 1834\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = British\n| party            = [[Whig (British political faction)|Whig]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Trinity College, Cambridge]]\n| spouse           = (1) [[Elizabeth Smith-Stanley, Countess of Derby|Lady Elizabeth Hamilton]] (1753\u20131797) <br/> [[Elizabeth Farren]] <br/>(d. 1829)\n| children         = [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 13th Earl of Derby]]<br>Lady Charlotte Hornby<br>Lady Elizabeth Henrietta Cole\n| parents          = [[James Smith-Stanley, Lord Strange]]<br>Lucy Smith\n}}\n'''Edward Smith-Stanley, 12th Earl of Derby''' [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] (1 September 1752 ([[Old Style and New Style dates|O.S.]])<ref>Edward was born on 1 September 1752 according to his entry in the [[Parish register|baptismal register]] of [[St John's Minster, Preston|St John's church, Preston]]: see {{cite web |title=The Parish of St John, Preston in the County of Lancashire |publisher=Lancashire OnLine Parish Clerks |accessdate=5 July 2018 |url=http://www.lan-opc.org.uk/Preston/Preston/stjohn/index.html}}{{cite book |url=https://www.familysearch.org/search/catalog/results?count=20&query=%2Bfilm_number%3A1278740 |title=Parish registers for St. John's Church, Preston, 1642\u20131948 |publisher=Church of England, St. John's Church | location = Preston, Lancashire |date=30 April 2005 |access-date=7 July 2018}} Online; electronic images of LDS microfilm 1278740, image 418 of 2102 ([https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Edward_Smith-Stanley_birth_register_extract.png closeup of entry]) Two days after his birth, the provisions of the [[Calendar (New Style) Act 1750]] came into effect, as Britain [[Old Style and New Style dates|converted to the Gregorian calendar]], so that Wednesday, 2 September was immediately followed by Thursday, 14 September. In many modern [[secondary source]]s (e.g. Cokayne ''et al.'' 1916; Brooke 1964; Cox 1974, p. 15; Crosby 2004) his birth date is given as 12 September 1752, which is a retrospective conversion of 1 September to the [[Old Style and New Style dates|New Style calendar]].</ref> \u2013 21 October 1834), usually styled '''Lord Stanley''' from 1771 to 1776, was a [[British peerage|British peer]] and politician of the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries. He held office as [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] in 1783 in the [[Fox\u2013North coalition]] and between 1806 and 1807 in the [[Ministry of All the Talents]].\n\n==Background and education==\nDerby was the son of [[James Smith-Stanley, Lord Strange]] (1716\u20131771), son of [[Edward Stanley, 11th Earl of Derby]] (1689-1776). His mother was Lucy Smith, a daughter and co-heiress of Hugh Smith of [[Weald Hall]], Essex. His father had assumed the additional surname and arms of Smith by private [[Act of Parliament]] in 1747.<ref>Act (1747) 21 Geo.2 c.''4'' \"Enabling James Stanley, Lord Strange, and his issue to take the surname Smith and to bear the arms of Smith and Heriz\" [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/changes/chron-tables/private/12]</ref> Derby entered [[Eton College]] in 1764, proceeding to [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] in 1771.<ref>{{acad|id=STNY771E|name=Stanley, the Hon. Edward (Smith)}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nDerby was returned to Parliament as one of two representatives for [[Lancashire (UK Parliament constituency)|Lancashire]] in 1774, a seat he held until 1776,<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/stanley-edward-1752-1834| title= Stanley, Edward, Lord Stanley (1752\u20131834) | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 15 November 2017}}</ref> when he succeeded his grandfather in the earldom and entered the [[House of Lords]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\">http://www.thepeerage.com/p10990.htm#i109895</ref> He served as [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]] between April and December 1783<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/><ref name=\"gazette\">{{London Gazette |issue=12470 |date=26 August 1783 |page=1 }}</ref> in the [[Fox-North Coalition]] headed by the [[William Cavendish-Bentinck, 3rd Duke of Portland|Duke of Portland]] and was sworn into the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] the same year.<ref name=\"gazette\"/> He remained out of office for the next 23 years but was once again Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster between 1806 and 1807 in the [[Ministry of All the Talents]] headed by [[William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville|Lord Grenville]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\nLord Derby also served as [[Lord Lieutenant of Lancashire]] between 1776 and 1834.<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/> He was also listed as a subscriber to the [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]] navigation in 1791.<ref>{{cite book | title = A list of the subscribers to the intended Bolton Bury and Manchester Canal Navigation | publisher = Manchester, Bolton and Bury Canal Company | year = 1791 | location = Greater Manchester County Records Office, ref. E4/78/419}}</ref>\n\n==Horse racing==\nAt a dinner party in 1778 held on his estate [[Oaks Park, Carshalton|\"The Oaks\"]] in [[Carshalton]], Lord Derby and his friends planned a [[sweepstake]] [[horse race]], won the following year by Derby's own horse, [[Bridget (horse)|Bridget]]. The race, [[Epsom Oaks|The Oaks]], has been named after the estate since. At a celebration after Bridget's win, a similar race for colts was proposed and Derby tossed a coin with [[Sir Charles Bunbury, 6th Baronet|Sir Charles Bunbury]] for the honour of naming the race. Derby won, and the race became known as the [[Epsom Derby|Derby Stakes]]. Bunbury won the initial race in 1780 with his horse, [[Diomed]]; Derby himself won it in 1787 with [[Sir Peter Teazle]].<ref>[http://www.tbheritage.com/Portraits/SirPeterTeazle.htm Thoroughbred Heritage: Sir Peter Teazle] Retrieved 23 November 2010</ref>\n\nHis [[Horse-racing colours|racing colours]] were black with a white cap.<ref name=RC1801>{{cite journal|last=Weatherby|first=Edward and James|journal=Racing Calendar|title=Colours worn by the riders of the following noblemen, gentlemen, &c.|year=1801 |volume=28|page=52|url=https://play.google.com/books/reader?id=jeMNAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&output=reader&hl=en_GB&pg=GBS.PP1}}</ref>\n\nHis influence on racing has been described as \"crucial\".<ref name=Barrett1995>{{cite book |title=The Daily Telegraph Chronicle of Horse Racing |editor-last=Barrett |editor-first=Norman |location=Enfield, Middlesex |publisher=Guinness Publishing |year=1995 |page=}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n[[File:Edward Smith Stanley (1752\u20131834), Twelfth Earl of Derby, with His First Wife (Lady Elizabeth Hamilton, 1753\u20131797) and Their Son (Edward Smith Stanley, 1775\u20131851) MET DP169403.jpg|thumb|right|''Edward Smith Stanley, Twelfth Earl of Derby, with His First Wife (Lady Elizabeth Hamilton) and Their Son'', portrait painting by [[Angelica Kauffmann]], ca 1776]]\nLord Derby married [[Elizabeth Smith-Stanley, Countess of Derby|Lady Elizabeth]], daughter of [[James Hamilton, 6th Duke of Hamilton]], on 23 June 1774. She bore him three children, being:\n* [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 13th Earl of Derby]] (21 April 1775 \u2013 30 June 1851); married his cousin Charlotte Margaret Hornby, daughter of Reverend Geoffrey Hornby by his wife, the Hon. Elizabeth Hornby (n\u00e9e Smith-Stanley)\n* Lady Charlotte (17 October 1776 \u2013 25 November 1805); married her cousin Edmund Hornby, Esq., son of Reverend Geoffrey Hornby by his wife, the Hon. Elizabeth Hornby (n\u00e9e Smith-Stanley)\n* Lady Elizabeth Henrietta (29 April 1778 \u2013 ca. 1857); married Thomas Cole, Esq., and had issue.\n\nIn the late 1770s, Lady Derby had a very public affair with [[John Frederick Sackville, 3rd Duke of Dorset]]. In 1779, the countess moved out of Lord Derby's house, leaving their children behind, apparently expecting that her husband would agree to a divorce and that the Duke would then marry her. About one year after she left his house, Lord Derby made it known that he had no intention of divorcing his wife; at the same time, he continued to deny her access to her children. The countess was socially ostracised for the remainder of her life. Historian Peter Thomson suggests that the third of the couple's children, Lady Elizabeth Henrietta, was the result of Lady Derby's affair with Dorset. Despite this, the Earl of Derby cared for the child after his wife left him.{{sfn|Thomson|2004}}\n\nLady Derby died at the age of 44 on 14 March 1797. Only six weeks later, on 1 May 1797, Lord Derby married the actress [[Elizabeth Farren]], daughter of George Farren. She bore him a daughter, Lady Mary Margaret Stanley,  (who married [[Thomas Egerton, 2nd Earl of Wilton]]) and died on 23 April 1829. Lord Derby survived her by five years and died on 21 October 1834, aged 82. He was succeeded in the earldom by his son from his first marriage, [[Edward Smith-Stanley, 13th Earl of Derby|Edward, Lord Stanley]].<ref name=\"thepeerage.com\"/>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Lady Elizabeth Hamilton (1753\u20131797), Countess of Derby.jpg|''Portrait of Lady Elizabeth Hamilton, countess of Derby'', by [[George Romney (painter)|George Romney]], ca 1776-1778\nFile:Portrait of Elizabeth Farren, by Thomas Lawrence.jpg|''Portrait of Elizabeth Farren'', by [[Thomas Lawrence]], 1790\nFile:Arms of the Earl of Derby 02666.jpg|Arms of Stanley,  Earl of Derby: ''Argent, on a bend azure three buck's heads cabossed or''. Painted in 1781\n\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n[[File:Peep-at-Christies-Gillray.jpeg|thumb|right|200px|In ''A Peep at [[Christie's|Christies']]'' (1796), [[James Gillray]] caricatured Lord Derby (as \"Tally-ho\") next to his future wife, [[Elizabeth Farren]]]]\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n*{{cite book |first=John |last=Brooke |chapter=Stanley, Edward, Lord Stanley (1752\u20131834) |editor1-first=Lewis |editor1-last=Namier |editor1-link=Lewis Namier |editor2-first=John |editor2-last=Brooke |title=The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1754\u20131790 |publisher=Secker & Warburg |location=London |volume=3 |year=1964 |pages=467\u20138 |url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1754-1790/member/stanley-edward-1752-1834 }}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=Cokayne |editor1-first=George Edward |editor1-link=George Edward Cokayne |editor2-last=Gibbs |editor2-first=Vicary |editor2-link=Vicary Gibbs (St Albans MP) |editor3-last=Doubleday |editor3-first=H. Arthur |year=1916 |title=Complete Peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and th