/wiki/Edward_Smith-Stanley,_12th_Earl_of_Derby"}
{"title_page": "2003 Hong Kong Sevens", "text_new": "{{Infobox Rugby Sevens\n| series = <small>'''[[2002\u201303 IRB Sevens World Series|IRB Sevens IV]]'''</small>\n| countries = {{flag|Hong Kong}}\n| date = 28\u201330 March 2003\n| champions1 = {{ru7|ENG}}\n| runnersup1 = {{ru7|NZL}}\n| champions2 = {{ru7|CAN}}\n| runnersup2 = {{ru7|SCO}}\n| champions3 = {{ru7|USA}}\n| runnersup3 = {{ru7|JPN}}\n| matches = 45\n| tries = \n| top point scorer = \n| top try scorer = \n| prevseason = [[2002 Hong Kong Sevens|2002]]\n| nextseason = [[2004 Hong Kong Sevens|2004]]\n}}\nThe '''2003 Hong Kong Sevens''' was an international [[rugby sevens]] tournament that took place at the [[Hong Kong Stadium]] between 28\u201330 March 2003. It was the 28th edition of the [[Hong Kong Sevens]] and was the fifth tournament of the [[2002\u201303 IRB Sevens World Series]]. Twenty-four teams competed in the tournament and were separated into six groups of four with the top eight teams qualifying through to the cup tournament.\n\nDue to the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] that was occurring in Hong Kong, some teams delayed their arrival to the country with three teams ([[Argentina national rugby sevens team|Argentina]], [[France national rugby sevens team|France]] and [[Italy national rugby sevens team|Italy]] withdrawing from the competition.\n\n[[England national rugby sevens team|England]] defended their Hong Kong title that they won the [[2002 Hong Kong Sevens|previous year]] defeating [[New Zealand national rugby sevens team|New Zealand]] in the final by a score of 22\u201317. The plate-final saw [[Canada national rugby sevens team|South Africa]] defeat [[Scotland national rugby sevens team|Scotland]] while the [[United States national rugby sevens team|United States]] took home the bowl defeating [[Japan national rugby sevens team|Japan]].\n\n==Teams==\nCompared to other tournament of the series, the Hong Kong Sevens had 24 teams compete for the title instead of the regular sixteen teams that usually competed in a World Series event. The tournament saw three teams withdraw after the official draw was revealed on February 27 due to the SARS outbreak that was occurring in South-East Asia. On March 21, France and Italy withdrew from the competition with Argentina withdrawing two days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/45645.html|title=Italy and France pull out of 7s|date=21 March 2003|publisher=ESPN Scrumn|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/45690.html|title=Pumas latest to pull out of Hong Kong\n|date=23 March 2003|publisher=ESPN Scrumn|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> They were replaced by [[Namibia national rugby sevens team|Namibia]], [[Tonga national rugby sevens team|Tonga]] and the [[Netherlands national rugby sevens team|Netherlands]] respectively. Other teams delayed their arrivals to Hong Kong with [[Fiji national rugby sevens team|Fiji]] and New Zealand only arriving three days before the tournament started.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/article/410430/fiji-and-new-zealand-arrivals-offset-argentina-pullout|title=Fiji and New Zealand arrivals offset Argentina pullout|first=Alvin|last=Sallay|date=25 March 2003|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* {{ru7|AUS}}\n* {{ru7|CAN}}\n* {{ru7|CHN}}\n* {{ru7|COK}}\n* {{ru7|TPE}}\n* {{ru7|ENG}}\n* {{ru7|FIJ}}\n* {{ru7|HKG}}\n* {{ru7|JPN}}\n* {{ru7|KEN}}\n* {{ru7|MAS}}\n* {{ru7|NAM}}\n* {{ru7|NED}}\n* {{ru7|NZL}}\n* {{ru7|RUS}}\n* {{ru7|SAM}}\n* {{ru7|SCO}}\n* {{ru7|SIN}}\n* {{ru7|RSA}}\n* {{ru7|KOR}}\n* {{ru7|SRI}}\n* {{ru7|TGA}}\n* {{ru7|USA}}\n* {{ru7|WAL}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Format==\nThe teams were drawn into six pools of four teams each. Each team played the other teams in their pool once, with three points awarded for a win, two points for a draw, and one point for a loss (no points awarded for a forfeit). The pool stage was played over the first two days of the tournament. The top team from each pool along with the two best runners-up advanced to the Cup quarter finals. The remaining four runners-up along with the four best third-placed teams advanced to the Plate quarter finals. The remaining eight teams went on to the Bowl quarter finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hksevens.com.hk/schedule_results/pool_format.htm|title=Format|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20030417153208/http://www.hksevens.com.hk/schedule_results/pool_format.htm|archive-date=17 April 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Pool stage==\nThe draw for the 2003 Hong Kong Sevens was held on 27 February 2003 with the revised draw occurring on the 25 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkrugby.com/eng/news/rugby_talk/APRIL-2003.pdf|title=All Set for Super Sevens|page=6|publisher=[[Hong Kong Rugby Union]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20050522183146/http://www.hkrugby.com/eng/news/rugby_talk/APRIL-2003.pdf|archive-date=22 May 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/45730.html|title=Revised HK 7s Draw|date=25 March 2003|publisher=ESPN Scrum|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|Key to colours in group tables\n|-\n|style=\"background:#cfc; width:20px;\"|\n|align=left|Teams that advanced to the Cup quarterfinals\n|-\n|\n|align=left|Teams that advanced to the Plate quarterfinals\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ffddbb; width:20px;\"|\n|align=left|Teams that advanced to the Bowl quarterfinals\n|-\n|}\n\n===Pool A===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=25 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=25 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=25 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=25 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=32 abbr=\"Points for\" |PF\n!width=32 abbr=\"Points against\" |PA\n!width=32 abbr=\"Points difference\" |PD\n!width=25 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|- bgcolor=\"#ccffcc\" \n|align=left|{{ru7|NZL}}