ll>|{{ru7|AUS}}|14|{{ru7|ENG}}|19\n<!-- semi finals -->\n|<small>30 March \u2013 [[Hong Kong Stadium]]</small>|{{ru7|NZL}}|21|{{ru7|RSA}}|17\n|<small>30 March \u2013 [[Hong Kong Stadium]]</small>|{{ru7|FIJ}}|19|{{ru7|ENG}}|24\n<!-- final -->\n|<small>30 March \u2013 [[Hong Kong Stadium]]</small>|{{ru7|NZL}}|17|{{ru7|ENG}}|22\n<!-- column widths -->\n|team-width=170|score-width=50\n}}\n<small>Source: [http://web.archive.org/web/20030402095651/http://www.hksevens.com.hk/schedule_results/results-finals.htm HK Sevens]</small>\n\n==Tournament placings==\n{{col-float|firstcol=20em}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; padding-bottom:0;\"\n! Place\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{noflag}}Team\n! Points\n|-\n| {{gold1}}\n|align=left| {{Ru7|ENG}} || 30\n|-\n| {{silver2}}\n|align=left| {{Ru7|NZL}} || 24\n|-\n| rowspan=2| {{bronze3}}\n|align=left| {{Ru7|FIJ}} || 18\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|RSA}} || 18\n|-\n| rowspan=4| 5\n|align=left| {{Ru7|AUS}} || 8\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|KEN}} || 8\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|SAM}} || 8\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|TGA}} || 8\n|-\n| 9\n|align=left| {{Ru7|CAN}} || 4\n|-\n| 10\n|align=left| {{Ru7|SCO}} || 3\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 11\n|align=left| {{Ru7|COK}} || 2\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|KOR}} || 2\n|}\n\n{{col-float-break}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; padding-bottom:0;\"\n! Place\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{noflag}}Team\n! Points\n|-\n| rowspan=4| 13\n|align=left| {{Ru7|TPE}} || 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|HKG}} || 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|NAM}} || 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|WAL}} || 0\n|-\n| 17\n|align=left| {{Ru7|USA}} || 1\n|-\n| 18\n|align=left| {{Ru7|JPN}} || 0\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 19\n|align=left| {{Ru7|CHN}} || 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|RUS}} || 0\n|-\n| rowspan=4| 21\n|align=left| {{Ru7|MAS}} || 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|NED}} || 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|SIN}} || 0\n|-\n|align=left| {{Ru7|SRI}} || 0\n|}\n{{col-float-end}}\n<small>Source: [http://www.rugby7.com/IRBS.asp?Y=2003 Rugby7.com]</small>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-other|[[2002\u201303 IRB Sevens World Series|IRB Sevens IV]]}}\n{{succession box|title= 2003 Hong Kong Sevens|before=[[2003 Wellington Sevens]]|after=[[2003 Cardiff Sevens]]}}\n{{s-other|[[Hong Kong Sevens]]}}\n{{succession box|title= 2003 Hong Kong Sevens|before=[[2002 Hong Kong Sevens]]|after=[[2004 Hong Kong Sevens]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n<!--{{2002\u201303 World Sevens Series}}-->\n{{Hong Kong Sevens}}\n\n[[Category:Hong Kong Sevens]]\n[[Category:2003 in Hong Kong sport|Hong Kong Sevens]]\n[[Category:2003 in Asian rugby union|Hong Kong Sevens]]\n[[Category:2002\u201303 IRB Sevens World Series|Hong Kong Sevens]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Rugby Sevens\n| series = <small>'''[[2002\u201303 IRB Sevens World Series|IRB Sevens IV]]'''</small>\n| countries = {{flag|Hong Kong}}\n| date = 28\u201330 March 2003\n| champions1 = {{ru7|ENG}}\n| runnersup1 = {{ru7|NZL}}\n| champions2 = {{ru7|CAN}}\n| runnersup2 = {{ru7|SCO}}\n| champions3 = {{ru7|USA}}\n| runnersup3 = {{ru7|JPN}}\n| matches = 45\n| tries = \n| top point scorer = \n| top try scorer = \n| prevseason = [[2002 Hong Kong Sevens|2002]]\n| nextseason = [[2004 Hong Kong Sevens|2004]]\n}}\nThe '''2003 Hong Kong Sevens''' was an international [[rugby sevens]] tournament that took place at the [[Hong Kong Stadium]] between 28\u201330 March 2003. It was the 28th edition of the [[Hong Kong Sevens]] and was the fifth tournament of the [[2002\u201303 IRB Sevens World Series]]. Twenty-four teams competed in the tournament and were separated into six groups of four with the top eight teams qualifying through to the cup tournament.\n\nDue to the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]] that was occuring in Hong Kong, some teams delayed their arrival to the country with three teams ([[Argentina national rugby sevens team|Argentina]], [[France national rugby sevens team|France]] and [[Italy national rugby sevens team|Italy]] withdrawing from the competition.\n\n[[England national rugby sevens team|England]] defended their Hong Kong title that they won the [[2002 Hong Kong Sevens|previous year]] defeating [[New Zealand national rugby sevens team|New Zealand]] in the final by a score of 22\u201317. The plate-final saw [[Canada national rugby sevens team|South Africa]] defeat [[Scotland national rugby sevens team|Scotland]] while the [[United States national rugby sevens team|United States]] took home the bowl defeating [[Japan national rugby sevens team|Japan]].\n\n==Teams==\nCompared to other tournament of the series, the Hong Kong Sevens had 24 teams compete for the title instead of the regular sixteen teams that usually competed in a World Series event. The tournament saw three teams withdraw after the official draw was revealed on February 27 due to the SARS outbreak that was occuring in South-East Asia. On March 21, France and Italy withdrew from the competition with Argentina withdrawing two days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/45645.html|title=Italy and France pull out of 7s|date=21 March 2003|publisher=ESPN Scrumn|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/45690.html|title=Pumas latest to pull out of Hong Kong\n|date=23 March 2003|publisher=ESPN Scrumn|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> They were replaced by [[Namibia national rugby sevens team|Namibia]], [[Tonga national rugby sevens team|Tonga]] and the [[Netherlands national rugby sevens team|Netherlands]] repectively. Other teams delayed their arrivals to Hong Kong with [[Fiji national rugby sevens team|Fiji]] and New Zealand only arriving three days before the tournament started.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/article/410430/fiji-and-new-zealand-arrivals-offset-argentina-pullout|title=Fiji and New Zealand arrivals offset Argentina pullout|first=Alvin|last=Sallay|date=25 March 2003|publisher=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* {{ru7|AUS}}\n* {{ru7|CAN}}\n* {{ru7|CHN}}\n* {{ru7|COK}}\n* {{ru7|TPE}}\n* {{ru7|ENG}}\n* {{ru7|FIJ}}\n* {{ru7|HKG}}\n* {{ru7|JPN}}\n* {{ru7|KEN}}\n* {{ru7|MAS}}\n* {{ru7|NAM}}\n* {{ru7|NED}}\n* {{ru7|NZL}}\n* {{ru7|RUS}}\n* {{ru7|SAM}}\n* {{ru7|SCO}}\n* {{ru7|SIN}}\n* {{ru7|RSA}}\n* {{ru7|KOR}}\n* {{ru7|SRI}}\n* {{ru7|TGA}}\n* {{ru7|USA}}\n* {{ru7|WAL}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Format==\nThe teams were drawn into six pools of four teams each. Each team played the other teams in their pool once, with three points awarded for a win, two points for a draw, and one point for a loss (no points awarded for a forfeit). The pool stage was played over the first two days of the tournament. The top team from each pool along with the two best runners-up advanced to the Cup quarter finals. The remaining four runners-up along with the four best third-placed teams advanced to the Plate quarter finals. The remaining eight teams went on to the Bowl quarter finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hksevens.com.hk/schedule_results/pool_format.htm|title=Format|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20030417153208/http://www.hksevens.com.hk/schedule_results/pool_format.htm|archive-date=17 April 2003}}</ref>\n\n==Pool stage==\nThe draw for the 2003 Hong Kong Sevens was held on 27 February 2003 with the revised draw occuring on the 25 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hkrugby.com/eng/news/rugby_talk/APRIL-2003.pdf|title=All Set for Super Sevens|page=6|publisher=[[Hong Kong Rugby Union]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20050522183146/http://www.hkrugby.com/eng/news/rugby_talk/APRIL-2003.pdf|archive-date=22 May 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/45730.html|title=Revised HK 7s Draw|date=25 March 2003|publisher=ESPN Scrum|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|Key to colours in group tables\n|-\n|style=\"background:#cfc; width:20px;\"|\n|align=left|Teams that advance