/paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190707.2.111\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>| away = City\n| try1 = D Norgrove\n| con1 = E McGregor\n| pen1 = E McGregor\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = Postlewaight, Harry Francis\n| stadium = Victoria Park 1\n| attendance = 7000\n| referee = Eddowes\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 5 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Maritime\n| score = 8-8\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =North Shore and Maritime 8 A Piece\n| page =8\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 160\n| date = 1919-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190707.2.111\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>\n| away = North Shore\n| try1 = [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], A Sutton\n| con1 = [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]]\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Scott, Nelson\n| con2 = Ernie Bailey\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park 2\n| attendance = 7000\n| referee = [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]]\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 5 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Newton\n| score = 27-3\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Marist Old Boys Big Defeat by Newton\n| page =8\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 160\n| date = 1919-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190707.2.111\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>\n| away = Marist\n| try1 = Newdick, Manson, Keenan 3, McLiver\n| con1 = Keenan, Isles\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Morton\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park 3\n| attendance = 7000\n| referee = Hill\n}}\n \n===Round 10===\nRound 10 featured two rarities. The Newton v North Shore match was played as a curtain-raiser to the Ponsonby v Maritime match on Auckland Domain 1. When matches were normally played at the same venue they all were played at the same time of 3pm on adjacent fields. In the 3rd match due to be played on the Domain the referee, F Thompson failed to turn up and after waiting for 40 minutes the decision was made to abandon the game. It was later revealed that he had been called away on an urgent business matter and had tried to contact the league but been unable to. The Auckland Rugby League accepted his explanation. The round was also significant for another reason. [[Craddock Dufty]] also debuted for Newton and kicked 2 conversions. He was to go on to represent New Zealand 12 times along with touring with the New Zealand Maori side.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 12 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 3-3\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Tight Struggle/Maritime 3, Ponsonby 3\n| page =8\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 166\n| date = 1919-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190714.2.96\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>\n| away = Maritime\n| try1 = A Cadman\n| con1 =\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Bert Avery]]\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain 1\n| attendance =\n| referee = W Murray\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 12 July\n| time = 1:30\n| home = Newton\n| score = 22-0\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Newton Vanquishes Shore\n| page =8\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 166\n| date = 1919-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190714.2.96\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>\n| away = North Shore\n| try1 = Iles 3, McSweeney 2, Condon\n| con1 = [[Craddock Dufty]] 2\n| pen1 =\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance =\n| referee =\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 12 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = Abandoned\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Tight Struggle/Maritime 3, Ponsonby 3/Newton Vanquishes Shore\n| page =8\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 166\n| date = 1919-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190714.2.96\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>\n| away = Marist\n| try1 =\n| con1 =\n| pen1 =\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance =\n| referee = F Thompson (did not arrive)\n}}\n\n===Round 4 Postponed Match===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 20 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 11-2\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Under League Rules/Ponsonby 11, Marist Old Boys 2/A Well Contested Game\n| page = 5\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17218\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190722.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-02-12}}</ref>\n| away = Marist\n| try1 = E McGregor, A Cross, S Chatfield\n| con1 = Unknown x 1\n| pen1 =\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = Unknown x 1\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance =\n| referee =\n}}\n\n==Roope Rooster Knockout Competition==\nThe round 1 match between [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] and [[Newton Rangers]] was abandoned towards the end with [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] leading by 12 points to 10 after [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]] supporters encroached on the field in protest against the referee and refused to move back. [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]] recorded their first competitive win in their history with a round 1 win over [[North Shore Albions]]. The final was won by [[Newton Rangers]] after they defeated Maritime by 8 points to 5.\n===Round 1===\nIn the Newton match with Ponsonby there was no crossbar and so they tied a piece of string between the two posts to act as a makeshift marker for kicks at goal.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 26 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Maritime\n| score = 14-6\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maritime Defeats City/Maritime V City\n| page =7\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17223\n| date = 1919-07-28\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190728.2.109.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-15}}</ref>| away = City\n| try1 = [[Bert Avery]] 2, Lang 2\n| con1 = Lang, Unknown x 1\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Clarke, Harry Francis\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain 1\n| attendance =\n| referee = A Ball\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 26 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Newton\n| score = 10-8*\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Ponsonby V Newton Undecided\n| page =7\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17223\n| date = 1919-07-28\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190728.2.109.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-15}}</ref>| away = Ponsonby\n| try1 = Isles, Thomas\n| con1 = [[Craddock Dufty]]\n| pen1 = [[Craddock Dufty]]\n| try2 = A Cadman, Brien\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = A Cross\n| stadium = Auckland Domain 2\n| attendance =\n| referee = Murray\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 26 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Marist\n| score = 17-3\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Marist Old Boys 17: North Shore 3/Notes on the Game/Marist Old Boys V North Shore\n| page =7\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17223\n| date = 1919-07-28\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190728.2.109.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-15}}</ref>| away = North Shore\n| try1 = White, Keenan 2\n| con1 = Clarke, W Ghent\n| pen1 = Clarke\n| drop1 = Robertson\n| try2 = L Boon\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain 3\n| attendance =\n| referee = Eddowes\n}}\n \n===Round 1 Replay===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 2 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Newton\n| score = 12-10\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Eight Thousand People Watch Newton Down Ponsonby/With a Two-Point Margin\n| page =8\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 183\n| date = 1919-08-04\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190804.2.64\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>\n| away = Ponsonby\n| try1 = Isles, [[Wally Somers]]\n| con1 = [[Craddock Dufty]]\n| pen1 = [[Craddock Dufty]]\n| drop1 = [[Craddock Dufty]]\n| try2 = [[Sam Lowrie]], E McGregor\n| con2 = [[Thomas McClymont]]\n| pen2 =\n| drop2 = S McNamara\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance = 8000\n| referee = W Murray\n}}\n \n===Semi Final===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 16 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Maritime\n| score = 22-21\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maritime Win Semi-Final/Marist Old Boys Just Beaten\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17211\n| date = 1919-08-18\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190818.2.8.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>\n| away = Marist\n| try1 = [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]] 2, Grey 3, A Sutton\n| con1 = Yardley, A Sutton\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Hing, Harris, Mitchell, Eustace 2\n| con2 = Unknown x 2\n| pen2 = [[Neville St George]]\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance = 5000\n| referee = A Tobin\n}}\n \n===Final===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 30 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Newton\n| score = 8-5\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>\n| away = Maritime\n| try1 = [[Nelson Bass]], [[Wally Somers]]\n| con1 = Cloke\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Cargill\n| con2 = A Sutton\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance =\n| referee = A Ball\n}}\n\n==Top Try Scorers and Point Scorers==\nThe following point scoring lists include Senior Championship matches and the Roope Rooster competition matches only. [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]] the champion New Zealand sprinter, who represented New Zealand at the 1920 Olympics top scored with 64 points and he also led the league with 14 tries.\n\nSeveral teams featured multiple players with the same surname with many sets of brothers. As a result, some of the scoring lists are inaccurate. For example, George Isles was known to have scored 5 tries however 6 other tries were attributed to \"Isles\" which may have been him or his brother A Isles. Likewise City Rovers featured [[George Paki]] and his brother B Paki. B Paki was attributed a try while \"Paki\" scored 2 tries, while for Ponsonby L Cadman scored 1, A Cadman scored 2, and \"Cadman\" scored 3. Rather than guess who scored the tries these have been left as is in the scoring records. \n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Rank!!Player!!Team!!Tries\n|-\n|1||[[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]]||Maritime||14\n|-\n|2||A Sutton||Maritime||8\n|-\n|3||Keenan||Newton||7\n|-\n|4||McAneny||North Shore||6\n|-\n|5||[[Bert Avery]]||Maritime||5\n|-\n|5||S Chatfield||Ponsonby United||5\n|-\n|5||[[George Isles]]||Newton||5\n|-\n|8||R Clarke||City Rovers||4\n|-\n|8||Clarke||Newton||4\n|-\n|8||E McGregor||Ponsonby||4\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!Rank!!Player!!Team!!Tries!!Con!!Pen!!Mark!!Points\n|-\n|1||[[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]]||Maritime||14||8||2||1||64\n|-\n|2||McAneny||North Shore||6||4||3||1||34\n|-\n|3||A Sutton||Maritime||8||3||0||0||30\n|-\n|4||E McGregor||Ponsonby United||4||5||2||0||26\n|-\n|5||Keenan||Newton Rangers||7||1||0||0||23\n|-\n|6||[[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]||City Rovers||2||4||3||0||20\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Other Club Matches and Lower Grades==\n===Lower Grade Teams and Clubs===\nThere were 5 lower grades in 1919.\n*Devonport Presbyterian\n*W.Y.M.I.\n*Thames Old Boys\n*Sunnyside\n*Mangere Rangers\n*[[Manukau Magpies|Manukau]]\n*[[Northcote Tigers|Northcote Ramblers]]\n*Post and Telegraph\n*[[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]]\n\nGrades were made of the following teams with the winners in bold:\n*'''2nd grade''' \u2013 City Rovers, City Rovers B, Maritime, Otahuhu, North Shore Albion, '''Sunnyside''', and Mangere Rangers. \n*'''3rd grade''' \u2013 '''Manukau''', Ponsonby, Otahuhu.\n*'''4th grade''' \u2013 '''City Rovers''', Otahuhu, Sunnyside, Newton Rangers, Newton Rangers B, Manukau, Grafton Athletic, Richmond Rovers, Northcote Ramblers, Maritime, Post and Telegraph, Devonport Presbyterian, W.Y.M.I.\n*'''5th grade''' \u2013 '''City Rovers''', Sunnyside, Richmond Rovers A, Northcote Ramblers, Manukau, North Shore Albion, Ponsonby United A, Devonport Presbyterian, W.Y.M.I, Otahuhu.\n*'''6th grade''' \u2013 [[City Rovers]], Manukau, '''Ponsonby''', Richmond Rovers, Post and Telegraph, Devonport Presbyterian, North Shore Albion A.\n\n===Benefit Match for Albert Asher===\nA match was played on 27 September between Maritime and [[City Rovers]] with the proceeds going to the benefit of Mr. [[Opai Asher]], a league veteran who was incapacitated as the result of an accident. A match was also played between the [[Auckland Star]] and [[New Zealand Herald]]. It was won 23 points to 5 by the Star.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =\u201dStar\u201d V. \u201cHerald\u201d\n| page =8\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 231\n| date = 1919-09-29\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190929.2.73\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 27 September\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Maritime\n| score = 19-13\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =\u201dStar\u201d V. \u201cHerald\u201d\n| page =8\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 231\n| date = 1919-09-29\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190929.2.73\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>| away = City\n| try1 = Neville St George 3, A Sutton, E Grey\n| con1 = C Grey, [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]]\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Cole, Duggan, [[Maurice Wetherill]]\n| con2 = [[Maurice Wetherill]] 2\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park\n| attendance =\n| referee = Dempsey\n}}\n\n===St Johns Benefit Match===\nTo end the season a rugby union and rugby league match was played at the [[Auckland Domain]] for the benefit of the [[St John New Zealand|St. John Ambulance Brigade]], whose members regularly attend league and union matches to perform first aid to injured players. The rugby league match was between [[City Rovers|City]] and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby]], and was won by [[City Rovers|City]] 13\u201310.\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 4 October\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 13-10\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =End of Football Season\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 237\n| date = 1919-10-06\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19191006.2.120\n| accessdate = 2020-02-12}}</ref>\n| away = Ponsonby\n| try1 = Tate, S Davidson 2\n| con1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]\n| pen1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]\n| try2 = [[Thomas McClymont]], [[Sam Lowrie]]\n| con2 = [[Thomas McClymont]], Cook\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance =\n| referee = Eddowes\n}}\n\n===Maritime Tour===\nIn Mid October the Maritime senior team embarked on an end of season tour to Hawkes Bay. They played Petane and Ahuriri and had two comfortable victories. Ahuriri had won the Vigor Brown Shield and the Charity Cup and the match was reportedly played in front of a large crowd. After their return they traveled to Thames on October 18 to play in a series of exhibition matches along with the Richmond club though the results are unknown.\n\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 9 October\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Petane\n| score = 0-32\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maritime Defeats Petane\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 241\n| date = 1919-10-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19191010.2.105\n| accessdate = 2020-02-12}}</ref>\n| away =Maritime\n| try1 = \n| con1 = \n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Dougie McGregor]], E McGregor, A Sutton 2, Grey 2, Unknown x 2\n| con2 = E McGregor, Harry Francis, Unknown 2\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = McLean Park, Napier\n| attendance =\n| referee =\n}}\n\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 11 October\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Ahuriri\n| score = 3-37\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Maritime Team\u2019s Tour\n| page = 9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 243\n| date = 1919-10-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19191013.2.96\n| accessdate = 2020-02-12}}</ref>\n| away = Maritime\n| try1 = Unknown x 1\n| con1 = \n| pen1 =\n| try2 = C Grey 3, A Sutton 2, J McGregor 2, Shearer, McGregor\n| con2 = Shearer, McGregor 2, Harry Francis, Lunn\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Napier\n| attendance =\n| referee =\n}}\n\n==Representative Fixtures==\nOn the 14th of May the selectors conducted a trial match between Auckland A and B teams to help choose both an Auckland and New Zealand team. The B team won the match by 15 points to 14. The first representative fixture of the season was a match played against the [[New Zealand rugby league team|New Zealand]] team which was preparing to depart for their tour of [[Australia]]. The [[New Zealand rugby league team|New Zealand]] team won 25\u201319 at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 8,000. On 20 July [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] played a match at the [[Auckland Domain]] with a Returned Soldiers team as part of a \u201cPeace Day\u201d sports celebration involving sports from several different codes.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Peace Celebration Sports/Big Day in the Domain/Track Events and Field Games\n| page =9\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-19}}</ref>\n\nOn the 23rd of August [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] played against a team composed of available members of the [[New Zealand rugby league team|New Zealand]] team which had toured [[Australia]] earlier in the year. The [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team was composed of Auckland players who remained so in essence was largely a \u2018B\u2019 team. The match was played at [[Victoria Park, New Zealand|Victoria Park]] and resulted in a high scoring win to the \u2018NZ\u2019 team 45\u201330.\n\nThen on the 20th of September, [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] played against the touring [[Australian rugby league team|Australian]] side and were well defeated by 32 points to 8. The match was played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 18,000 spectators.\n\n===Auckland v New Zealand===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 24 May\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 19-25\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>\n| away = New Zealand\n| try1 = [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], A Sutton, R Clarke, Pullan, Penalty Try\n| con1 = Harry Francis, Phil Castles\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[Karl Ifwersen]] 3, [[Archie Waddell]]\n| con2 = [[Karl Ifwersen]] 3\n| pen2 = [[Karl Ifwersen]] 2\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance = 8000\n| referee = A Ball\n}}\n \n===Auckland v Returned Soldiers===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 20 July\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 24-26\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>\n| away = Returned Soldiers\n| try1 = [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]] 2, Isles 2, E McGregor, Unknown x 1\n| con1 = [[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]], Unknown x 2\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = Nicholson, [[Bert Laing]], George Neal, Thomas, [[Bert Avery]], Unknown x 3\n| con2 = Unknown x 1\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance =\n| referee = A Ball\n}}\n \n===Northern Union Challenge Cup===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 9 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 38-13\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>\n| away = Hawkes Bay\n| try1 = [[George Isles]] 2, [[Craddock Dufty]], [[Dougie McGregor]], [[Tom Haddon]] 3, Davidson\n| con1 = [[Craddock Dufty]] 7\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = J Atwood, N McCarthy, G Jackson\n| con2 = G Jackson\n| pen2 = N McCarthy\n| stadium = Eden Park\n| attendance = 9000\n| referee = A Ferguson\n}}\n \n===Auckland v New Zealand===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 23 August\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 30-45\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Touring Team V Auckland/Trial Game Before Selectors/Win for Traveller Players\n| page =4\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17247\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190825.2.7.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>| away = New Zealand\n| try1 = E McGregor, R Mitchell, Newdick, Yardley, Delaney 2, Cargill, A Ivil\n| con1 = E McGregor, Harry Francis, Delaney\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Dougie McGregor]], [[Thomas McClymont]] 2, [[Bill Cloke]], [[Jim Rukutai]], [[Wally Somers]] 2, Unknown x 4\n| con2 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]] 2, [[Thomas McClymont]], [[Bert Laing]] 2, Unknown x 1\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Victoria Park 1\n| attendance = 6500\n| referee = T Hill\n}}\n \n===Auckland v Australia===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 20 September\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Auckland\n| score = 8-32\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Another Aussie Win/Australia 32, Auckland 8/A Game of Incidents\n| page =8\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 225\n| date = 1919-09-22\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190922.2.88\n| accessdate = 2019-08-19}}</ref>| away = Australia\n| try1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[Bert Avery]]\n| con1 =\n| pen1 = [[Karl Ifwersen]]\n| try2 = L Cubitt 2, F Burge 4, Gilbert 2\n| con2 = C Fraser 2, R Norman 2\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance = 18000\n| referee = A Ball\n}}\n\n===Auckland Representative Matches Played and Scorers===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!No!!Name!!Club Team!!Play!!Tries!!Con!!Pen!!Points\n|-\n|1||[[Craddock Dufty]]||Newton Rangers||1||5||0||0||15\n|-\n|3||[[George Davidson (athlete)|George Davidson]]||Maritime||5||4||1||0||14\n|-\n|4||[[George Isles]]||Newton Rangers||3||4||0||0||12\n|-\n|5||[[Tom Haddon]]||City Rovers||1||3||0||0||9\n|-\n|6||Delaney||Marist Old Boys||1||2||1||0||8\n|-\n|6||E McGregor||Ponsonby United||2||2||1||0||8\n|-\n|8||Harry Francis||City Rovers||4||0||2||0||4\n|-\n|9||A Sutton||Maritime||1||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||R Clarke||City Rovers||1||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||R Mitchell||City Rovers||4||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||Newdick||Newton Rangers||2||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||[[Dougie McGregor]]||Grafton Athletic||2||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||[[Bert Avery]]||Maritime||2||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||Yardley||Maritime||1||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||Cargill||Maritime||1||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||A Ivil||Newton Rangers||1||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|9||[[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]||City Rovers||1||1||0||0||3\n|-\n|19||Phil Castles||Newton Rangers||2||0||1||0||2\n|-\n|19||[[Karl Ifwersen]]||Grafton Athletic||1||0||0||1||2\n|-\n|20||Keenan||Newton Rangers||3||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Frank Delgrosso]]||Ponsonby United||3||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Sam Lowrie]]||Ponsonby United||3||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||J Hing||Marist Old Boys||2||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||Ernie Bailey||North Shore Albions||2||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||A Cross||Maritime||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||Thomas||City Rovers||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Nelson Bass]]||Newton||2||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Ernie Herring]]||Grafton Athletic||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||? Cadman||Ponsonby United||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||H Wynn||City Rovers||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20|| G Delgrosso||Ponsonby United||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Bert Laing]]||City Rovers||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[George Neal]]||Newton Rangers||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Keith Helander]]||North Shore Albions||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Arthur Matthews (rugby league)|Arthur Matthews]]||North Shore Albions||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Thomas McClymont]]||Ponsonby United||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Ivan Stewart (rugby league)|Ivan Stewart]]||City Rovers||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||W Ghent||Grafton Athletic||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Stan Walters (rugby league)|Stan Walters]]||North Shore Albions||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[Bill Williams (rugby league)|Bill Williams]]||Newton Rangers||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|20||[[George Paki]]||City Rovers||1||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.aucklandleague.co.nz/ Auckland Rugby League Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Auckland Rugby League seasons]]\n[[Category:Rugby league in Auckland]]\n[[Category:Rugby league governing bodies in New Zealand]] \n[[Category:Rugby league]]\n|}\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAuckland Representative Matches Played and Scorers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1919_Auckland_Rugby_League_season"}
{"title_page": "Bobby Mitchell", "text_new": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Other people|Bobby Mitchell}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| image =\n| position = [[Halfback (American football)|Halfback]], [[Wide receiver|flanker]]\n| number = 49\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1935|6|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|4|5|1935|6|6}}\n| death_place =\n| draftyear = 1958\n| draftround = 7\n| draftpick = 84\n| high_school = Langston<br>(Hot Springs, Arkansas)\n| college = [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]]\n| teams =\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{NFL Year|1958}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1961}})\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1962}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1968}})\n|pastexecutive=\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1969}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2002}})\n| highlights =\n* 4\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1961 Pro Bowl|1960]], [[1963 Pro Bowl|1962]]\u2013[[1965 Pro Bowl|1964]])\n* 3\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1962 All-Pro Team|1962]]\u2013[[1964 All-Pro Team|1964]])\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team All-Pro ([[1959 All-Pro Team|1959]], [[1960 All-Pro Team|1960]])\n* [[List of NFL annual receptions leaders|NFL receptions leader]] (1962)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of NFL annual receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards leader]] (1962, 1963)\n* [[List of National Football League season receiving touchdown leaders|NFL receiving touchdowns leader]] (1964)\n* [[Washington Redskins#Redskins Ring of Fame|Washington Redskins Ring of Fame]]\n* [[Cleveland Browns Ring of Honor]]\n| statlabel1 = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n| statvalue1 = 521\n| statlabel2 = Receiving yards\n| statvalue2 = 7,955\n| statlabel3 = Receiving [[touchdown]]s\n| statvalue3 = 65\n| statlabel4 = Rushing yards\n| statvalue4 = 2,735\n| statlabel5 = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue5 = 18\n| statlabel6 = [[Return specialist|Return]] touchdowns\n| statvalue6 = 8\n| nfl = MIT650992\n| HOF = bobby-mitchell\n| pfr = M/MitcBo00\n}}\n\n'''Robert Cornelius Mitchell''' (June 6, 1935 \u2013 April 5, 2020) was an American professional [[American football|football]] player who was a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] and [[Wide receiver#Types|flanker]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[Cleveland Browns]] and the [[Washington Redskins]]. Mitchell became the Redskins' first [[African-American]] star after joining them in 1962, when they became the last NFL team to [[racial integration|integrate]].<ref name=goldstein_04052020/> He was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 1983.\n\n==Early life==\nMitchell was born in [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]], and attended Langston High School.<ref name=hofbiography>{{cite web | work=Pro Football Hall of Fame | url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/release.jsp?release_id=1382 | title=Bobby Mitchell, Class of 1983 | accessdate=June 27, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130020135/http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/release.jsp?release_id=1382|archivedate=January 30, 2009}}</ref> There, he played [[high school football|football]], [[basketball]], and [[Track and field|track]], and was good enough at [[baseball]] to be offered a contract with the [[St. Louis Cardinals]].<ref name=hofbiography />\n\n==College career==\nInstead of playing [[Major League Baseball|professional baseball]], Mitchell chose to attend the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]], which he picked from a host of schools that offered him scholarships.<ref name=hofbiography />  He played [[college football]] for the [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois Fighting Illini]] and had a particularly good sophomore year.  At the beginning of the [[1955 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|1955 season]], he was behind junior Harry Jefferson on the [[depth chart]].  Seven games into the season, Jefferson went down with an injury, and Mitchell took over at one of the halfback spots.<ref name=illini>{{cite web | work=University of Illinois Athletics | url=http://fightingillini.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/051107aay.html | title=Catching Up With Bobby Mitchell | accessdate=June 27, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231151640/http://fightingillini.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/051107aay.html | archive-date=December 31, 2007 | url-status=dead }}</ref>  The first time he handled the football, he ran 64 yards for a touchdown.<ref name=hofbiography />  Though he entered in the third quarter, Mitchell gained 173 yards in 10 carries, and the Illini upset third-ranked [[University of Michigan|Michigan]], 25-6.<ref name=illini />  He gained more than 100 yards in each of final two games of the season, when he also played as a [[defensive back]].<ref name=illini />  That year, he averaged a record 8.6 yards per rush.<ref name=hofbiography />\n\nAs a junior in [[1956 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|1956]], Mitchell did not see the field much due to a knee injury.<ref name=illini /> After [[1957 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|his senior season]], he was invited to play in the [[College All-Star Game]], where he got behind [[defensive back]], [[Jim David (American football)|James David]] on an 84-yard touchdown reception, and then scored again on an 18-yard pass from [[Jim Ninowski]].<ref name=hofbiography /> The All-Stars' upset the [[Detroit Lions]], 35-19, and Mitchell and Ninowski shared game [[Most Valuable Player|MVP]] honors.<ref name=hofbiography />  Mitchell was named first-team All-Big Ten football in 1955 and second-team status in 1957.<ref name=illini /> He was named to The Pigskin Club Honor Roll by [[The Pigskin Club of Washington, D.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|title=75th Annual Awards Dinner|publisher=The Pigskin Club of Washington, D.C.|year=2013|page=17|url=http://pigskinclub.com/images/PigskinClub-75thAnniversary-Final-compressed.pdf|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMitchell was even more successful in track.  In February 1958, he set an indoor world record (one that lasted only six days) with a 7.7 mark in the 70-yard low hurdles.<ref name=hofbiography /><ref name=illini />  In the [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] championships, he scored 13 points and helped Illinois win the title.<ref name=hofbiography />  Mitchell was unsure whether he wanted to pursue a career in football or track.  Even though the [[1960 Summer Olympics]] were still two years away, he had his sights set on competing on the American team.<ref name=hofbiography /> However, [[Cleveland Browns|Browns]] head coach [[Paul Brown]] offered to pay him $7,000 during his rookie season and was able to convince Mitchell to play football instead of participating in the Olympics.<ref>{{cite news | work=Washington Post | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/redskins/longterm/1997/history/allart/fame83.htm | title=Fame Catches Up With Ex-Redskins Mitchell, Jurgensen | accessdate=June 27, 2008 | date=July 23, 1998}}</ref>\n\n==NFL playing career==\n\n===Cleveland Browns (1958\u20131961)===\nMitchell was [[NFL Draft|drafted]] in the seventh round of the [[1958 NFL Draft]] by the [[Cleveland Browns]], where he played as a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]].<ref name=hofprofile>{{cite web | work=Pro Football Hall of Fame | url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PlayerId=152 | title=Bobby Mitchell's Pro Football HOF profile | accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref>  He was teamed with [[Jim Brown]] to give the Browns one of the most successful running back combinations from [[1958 Cleveland Browns season|1958]] through [[1961 Cleveland Browns season|1961]].<ref name=hofprofile />\n\nAs a rookie, Mitchell had a 98-yard kickoff return.  A year later against Washington, he rushed for 232 yards, including a 90-yard scoring scamper.  The same year, he returned a punt 78 yards against the [[New York Giants]].<ref name=hofbiography /> He earned his first [[Pro Bowl]] selection in [[1960 Cleveland Browns season|1960]].<ref name=washpost_obit>{{cite news|last1=Maske|first1=Mark|last2=Carpenter|first2=Les|title=Bobby Mitchell, Pro Football Hall of Famer and pioneering Redskins star, dies at 84|date=April 6, 2020|newspaper=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/bobby-mitchell-pro-football-hall-of-famer-and-pioneering-redskins-star-dies-at-84/2020/04/05/edc2a40e-77a2-11ea-b6ff-597f170df8f8_story.html|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a Brown, Mitchell accumulated 2297 yards rushing, 1463 yards receiving, 607 yards on punt returns, 1550 yards on kickoff returns, and scored 38 touchdowns.<ref name=hofbiography />  He once held the Browns' career record for kickoff returns for touchdowns, and he also currently holds the team's best rookie rushing average (6.3 in 1958).<ref>{{cite web | work=Cleveland Browns | url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/team/history/honor/bobby_mitchell.php | title=Bobby Mitchell's Cleveland Browns profile | accessdate=June 27, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080529192720/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/team/history/honor/bobby_mitchell.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = May 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Washington Redskins (1962\u20131968)===\nUnder pressure to [[racial integration|integrate]] the team by the [[federal government of the United States|U.S. federal goverment]], the [[Washington Redskins]] selected [[Ernie Davis]] with the first overall pick of the [[1962 NFL Draft]].<ref name=goldstein_04052020/><ref name=integrate>{{cite web | work=ESPN | url=http://espn.go.com/page2/wash/s/2002/0305/1346021.html | title=Civil Rights on the Gridiron | accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref>  However, Redskins owner [[George Preston Marshall]], wary of Davis's potential salary demands, traded his rights to the [[Cleveland Browns]] for Mitchell and first-round draft pick [[Leroy Jackson]].<ref name=goldstein_04052020/><ref name=integrate /><ref>{{cite news | work=Time Magazine | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873711,00.html | title=August 1962 Scoreboard | accessdate=June 27, 2008 | date=August 10, 1962|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219065054/https://time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873711,00.html|archivedate=February 19, 2011}}</ref>  Unbeknownst to anyone at the time of the draft, Davis had [[leukemia]], and died without ever playing a down in professional football.<ref name=integrate />  \n\nMitchell, along with [[John Nisby]] and [[Ron Hatcher]], was one of three black players on the [[1962 Washington Redskins season|1962 Redskins]], as the franchise became the last professional football team to integrate.<ref name=basen_10062012>{{cite news|last=Basen|first=Ryan|title=Fifty Years Ago, Last Outpost of Segregation in N.F.L. Fell|date=October 6, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/07/sports/football/50-years-ago-redskins-were-last-nfl-team-to-integrate.html|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> [[Bill McPeak]], in his first year as head coach, immediately announced Mitchell would become a [[Wide receiver#Types|flanker]].  In his first game in Washington, Mitchell ran back a 92-yard kickoff return against the [[Dallas Cowboys]].<ref name=hofbiography />  The Redskins finished the season with a 5\u20137\u20132 record, their best record in five years.<ref name=basen_10062012/> Mitchell led the league with 72 catches and 1384 yards and ranked third with 11 touchdowns.<ref name=hofbiography/><ref name=basen_10062012/> He was selected to the first of three consecutive Pro Bowls.<ref name=washpost_obit/>\n\nIn [[1963 NFL season|1963]], Mitchell recorded 69 catches for 1436 yards and seven more touchdowns. During this season, he also became the second player in league and franchise history to record a [[99-yard pass play]]. The pass from [[George Izo]] was the first 99-yard pass in over 23 years, when the Redskins' [[Frank Filchock]] and [[Andy Farkas]] set the original record October 15, 1939.<ref name=hofbiography />  During the next four years, Mitchell's reception totals were 60, 60, 58 and 60.<ref name=hofbiography />  In [[1967 NFL season|1967]], new head coach [[Otto Graham]] chose to move Mitchell back to [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] because of Graham's decision a year earlier to move the team's best running back, [[Charley Taylor]], to wide receiver.  Mitchell enjoyed only moderate success running the ball but he did catch 60 passes for 866 yards and six touchdowns.<ref name=hofbiography />\n\nIn [[1969 NFL season|1969]], [[Vince Lombardi]] became head coach and promised Mitchell that he would return him to flanker.<ref name=hofbiography />  But as [[National Football League Training Camp|training camp]] progressed, Mitchell realized that he was not in the same shape he once was and chose to retire.<ref name=hofbiography />\n\nDuring his first six seasons with the Redskins, Mitchell never caught fewer than 58 passes.<ref name=hofprofile />  When he retired, his 14,078 combined net yards was the second highest total in NFL history.<ref name=hofprofile />  He had also scored 91 touchdowns (18 by rushing, 65 on receptions, 3 on punt returns, and 5 on kickoff returns).  He amassed 7,954 yards on receptions and 2,735 yards on rushes.<ref name=hofprofile />  He was elected to the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 1983.<ref name=hofbiography/>\n\n==Front-office career (1969\u20132003)==\nAfter retiring from football in 1968, Mitchell remained with the Redskins, at the request of then [[head coach]] [[Vince Lombardi]], as a pro [[Scout (sport)|scout]].<ref name=frontoffice>{{cite web | work=St. Petersburg Times | url=http://www.sptimes.com/2003/02/01/Sports/Mitchell_leaves_Redsk.shtml | title=Mitchell leaves Redskins | accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref> He gradually moved up in the ranks to assistant [[general manager]] in the organization,<ref name=integrate/> and he aspired to become the NFL's first black GM.<ref name=frontoffice /> In 1978, Washington owner [[Edward Bennett Williams]] passed over Mitchell for the GM position in favor of [[Bobby Beathard]].<ref name=washpost_obit/><ref name=frontoffice /> Mitchell retired in 2003, stating that he was \"deeply hurt\" by how owner [[Jack Kent Cooke]] passed him over as the team's general manager in favor of [[Charley Casserly]] in 1998 and by coach [[Steve Spurrier]]'s decision to issue his No. 49 uniform number, which had not been issued for years though never [[retired number|retired]], to [[Leonard Stephens]] that season.<ref name=washpost_obit/><ref name=frontoffice />\n\nAs a player and a front office executive, Mitchell spent 41 years with the Redskins.<ref name=frontoffice />\n\n==Personal life==\nMitchell lived in [[Washington D.C.]] with his wife, Gwen who is an attorney. They had two children, Robert, Jr and Terri.<ref name=illini />\n\nBeginning in 1980, Mitchell hosted the Bobby Mitchell Hall of Fame Classic, an annual golf fundraiser that benefits the [[Leukemia & Lymphoma Society]].<ref>{{cite news | work=Washington Post | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/12/AR2005071201798_pf.html | title='Happy Because He Has Hope' | accessdate=June 27, 2008 | first=Walter | last=Gabriel}}</ref>\n\nMitchell also worked in many efforts and organizations, including the [[United Negro College Fund]], the [[Howard University]] Cancer Research Advisory Committee, the [[American Lung Association]] of D.C., the [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Day|Martin Luther King Jr. Holiday Commission]], the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys Club of Washington]], the [[National Urban League]], the [[NAACP]], the [[Junior Chamber of Commerce]], the University of Illinois Presidents Council and the University of Illinois Foundation.<ref name=illini />\n\nMitchell died at age 84 on April 5, 2020.<ref name=goldstein_04052020>{{cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Richard|title=Bobby Mitchell, Hall of Famer and the Redskins\u2019 First Black Star, Dies at 84|date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/sports/football/bobby-mitchell-dead.html|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Profootballhof|152|Bobby Mitchell}}\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=MIT650992 |cfl= |afl= |espn= |cbs= |yahoo= |fox= |si= |pfr=M/MitcBo00 |rotoworld=}}\n{{Browns1958DraftPicks}}\n{{NFL receiving touchdown leaders}}\n{{NFL receiving yardage leaders}}\n{{The 70 Greatest Redskins}}\n{{Washington Redskins Ring of Fame}}\n{{Washington Redskins}}\n{{1983 Football HOF}}\n{{Pro Football Hall of Fame members}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football halfbacks]]\n[[Category:American football return specialists]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n[[Category:Illinois Fighting Illini football players]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins executives]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins players]]\n[[Category:Eastern Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Hot Springs High School (Arkansas) alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hot Springs, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Arkansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Other people|Bobby Mitchell}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| image =\n| position = [[Halfback (American football)|Halfback]], [[Wide receiver|flanker]]\n| number = 49\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1935|6|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2020|4|5|1935|6|6}}\n| death_place =\n| draftyear = 1958\n| draftround = 7\n| draftpick = 84\n| high_school = Langston<br>(Hot Springs, Arkansas)\n| college = [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]]\n| teams =\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{NFL Year|1958}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1961}})\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1962}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1968}})\n|pastexecutive=\n* [[Washington Redskins]] ({{NFL Year|1969}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2002}})\n| highlights =\n* 4\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1961 Pro Bowl|1960]], [[1963 Pro Bowl|1962]]\u2013[[1965 Pro Bowl|1964]])\n* 3\u00d7 First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[1962 All-Pro Team|1962]]\u2013[[1964 All-Pro Team|1964]])\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team All-Pro ([[1959 All-Pro Team|1959]], [[1960 All-Pro Team|1960]])\n* [[List of NFL annual receptions leaders|NFL receptions leader]] (1962)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of NFL annual receiving yards leaders|NFL receiving yards leader]] (1962, 1963)\n* [[List of National Football League season receiving touchdown leaders|NFL receiving touchdowns leader]] (1964)\n* [[Washington Redskins#Redskins Ring of Fame|Washington Redskins Ring of Fame]]\n* [[Cleveland Browns Ring of Honor]]\n| statlabel1 = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n| statvalue1 = 521\n| statlabel2 = Receiving yards\n| statvalue2 = 7,955\n| statlabel3 = Receiving [[touchdown]]s\n| statvalue3 = 65\n| statlabel4 = Rushing yards\n| statvalue4 = 2,735\n| statlabel5 = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue5 = 18\n| statlabel6 = [[Return specialist|Return]] touchdowns\n| statvalue6 = 8\n| nfl = MIT650992\n| HOF = bobby-mitchell\n| pfr = M/MitcBo00\n}}\n\n'''Robert Cornelius Mitchell''' (June 6, 1935 \u2013 April 5, 2020) was an American professional [[American football|football]] player who was a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] and [[Wide receiver#Types|flanker]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[Cleveland Browns]] and the [[Washington Redskins]]. Mitchell became the Redskins' first [[African-American]] star after joining them in 1962, when they became the last NFL team to [[racial integration|integrate]].<ref name=goldstein_04052020/> He was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 1983.\n\n==Early life==\nMitchell was born in [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]], and attended Langston High School.<ref name=hofbiography>{{cite web | work=Pro Football Hall of Fame | url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/release.jsp?release_id=1382 | title=Bobby Mitchell, Class of 1983 | accessdate=June 27, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130020135/http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/release.jsp?release_id=1382|archivedate=January 30, 2009}}</ref> There, he played [[high school football|football]], [[basketball]], and [[Track and field|track]], and was good enough at [[baseball]] to be offered a contract with the [[St. Louis Cardinals]].<ref name=hofbiography />\n\n==College career==\nInstead of playing [[Major League Baseball|professional baseball]], Mitchell chose to attend the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]], which he picked from a host of schools that offered him scholarships.<ref name=hofbiography />  He played [[college football]] for the [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois Fighting Illini]] and had a particularly good sophomore year.  At the beginning of the [[1955 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|1955 season]], he was behind junior Harry Jefferson on the [[depth chart]].  Seven games into the season, Jefferson went down with an injury, and Mitchell took over at one of the halfback spots.<ref name=illini>{{cite web | work=University of Illinois Athletics | url=http://fightingillini.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/051107aay.html | title=Catching Up With Bobby Mitchell | accessdate=June 27, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231151640/http://fightingillini.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/051107aay.html | archive-date=December 31, 2007 | url-status=dead }}</ref>  The first time he handled the football, he ran 64 yards for a touchdown.<ref name=hofbiography />  Though he entered in the third quarter, Mitchell gained 173 yards in 10 carries, and the Illini upset third-ranked [[University of Michigan|Michigan]], 25-6.<ref name=illini />  He gained more than 100 yards in each of final two games of the season, when he also played as a [[defensive back]].<ref name=illini />  That year, he averaged a record 8.6 yards per rush.<ref name=hofbiography />\n\nAs a junior in [[1956 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|1956]], Mitchell did not see the field much due to a knee injury.<ref name=illini /> After [[1957 Illinois Fighting Illini football team|his senior season]], he was invited to play in the [[College All-Star Game]], where he got behind [[defensive back]], [[Jim David (American football)|James David]] on an 84-yard touchdown reception, and then scored again on an 18-yard pass from [[Jim Ninowski]].<ref name=hofbiography /> The All-Stars' upset the [[Detroit Lions]], 35-19, and Mitchell and Ninowski shared game [[Most Valuable Player|MVP]] honors.<ref name=hofbiography />  Mitchell was named first-team All-Big Ten football in 1955 and second-team status in 1957.<ref name=illini /> He was named to The Pigskin Club Honor Roll by [[The Pigskin Club of Washington, D.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|title=75th Annual Awards Dinner|publisher=The Pigskin Club of Washington, D.C.|year=2013|page=17|url=http://pigskinclub.com/images/PigskinClub-75thAnniversary-Final-compressed.pdf|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMitchell was even more successful in track.  In February 1958, he set an indoor world record (one that lasted only six days) with a 7.7 mark in the 70-yard low hurdles.<ref name=hofbiography /><ref name=illini />  In the [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] championships, he scored 13 points and helped Illinois win the title.<ref name=hofbiography />  Mitchell was unsure whether he wanted to pursue a career in football or track.  Even though the [[1960 Summer Olympics]] were still two years away, he had his sights set on competing on the American team.<ref name=hofbiography /> However, [[Cleveland Browns|Browns]] head coach [[Paul Brown]] offered to pay him $7,000 during his rookie season and was able to convince Mitchell to play football instead of participating in the Olympics.<ref>{{cite news | work=Washington Post | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/redskins/longterm/1997/history/allart/fame83.htm | title=Fame Catches Up With Ex-Redskins Mitchell, Jurgensen | accessdate=June 27, 2008 | date=July 23, 1998}}</ref>\n\n==NFL playing career==\n\n===Cleveland Browns (1958\u20131961)===\nMitchell was [[NFL Draft|drafted]] in the seventh round of the [[1958 NFL Draft]] by the [[Cleveland Browns]], where he played as a [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]].<ref name=hofprofile>{{cite web | work=Pro Football Hall of Fame | url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/member.aspx?PlayerId=152 | title=Bobby Mitchell's Pro Football HOF profile | accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref>  He was teamed with [[Jim Brown]] to give the Browns one of the most successful running back combinations from [[1958 NFL season|1958]] through [[1961 NFL season|1961]].<ref name=hofprofile />\n\nAs a rookie, Mitchell had a 98-yard kickoff return.  A year later against Washington, he rushed for 232 yards, including a 90-yard scoring scamper.  The same year, he returned a punt 78 yards against the [[New York Giants]].<ref name=hofbiography /> He earned his first [[Pro Bowl]] selection in [[1960 Cleveland Browns season|1960]].<ref name=washpost_obit>{{cite news|last1=Maske|first1=Mark|last2=Carpenter|first2=Les|title=Bobby Mitchell, Pro Football Hall of Famer and pioneering Redskins star, dies at 84|date=April 6, 2020|newspaper=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/redskins/bobby-mitchell-pro-football-hall-of-famer-and-pioneering-redskins-star-dies-at-84/2020/04/05/edc2a40e-77a2-11ea-b6ff-597f170df8f8_story.html|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs a Brown, Mitchell accumulated 2297 yards rushing, 1463 yards receiving, 607 yards on punt returns, 1550 yards on kickoff returns, and scored 38 touchdowns.<ref name=hofbiography />  He once held the Browns' career record for kickoff returns for touchdowns, and he also currently holds the team's best rookie rushing average (6.3 in 1958).<ref>{{cite web | work=Cleveland Browns | url=http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/team/history/honor/bobby_mitchell.php | title=Bobby Mitchell's Cleveland Browns profile | accessdate=June 27, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080529192720/http://www.clevelandbrowns.com/team/history/honor/bobby_mitchell.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = May 29, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Washington Redskins (1962\u20131968)===\nUnder pressure to [[racial integration|integrate]] the team by the [[federal government of the United States|U.S. federal goverment]], the [[Washington Redskins]] selected [[Ernie Davis]] with the first overall pick of the [[1962 NFL Draft]].<ref name=goldstein_04052020/><ref name=integrate>{{cite web | work=ESPN | url=http://espn.go.com/page2/wash/s/2002/0305/1346021.html | title=Civil Rights on the Gridiron | accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref>  However, Redskins owner [[George Preston Marshall]], wary of Davis's potential salary demands, traded his rights to the [[Cleveland Browns]] for Mitchell and first-round draft pick [[Leroy Jackson]].<ref name=goldstein_04052020/><ref name=integrate /><ref>{{cite news | work=Time Magazine | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873711,00.html | title=August 1962 Scoreboard | accessdate=June 27, 2008 | date=August 10, 1962|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219065054/https://time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873711,00.html|archivedate=February 19, 2011}}</ref>  Unbeknownst to anyone at the time of the draft, Davis had [[leukemia]], and died without ever playing a down in professional football.<ref name=integrate />  \n\nMitchell, along with [[John Nisby]] and [[Ron Hatcher]], was one of three black players on the [[1962 Washington Redskins season|1962 Redskins]], as the franchise became the last professional football team to integrate.<ref name=basen_10062012>{{cite news|last=Basen|first=Ryan|title=Fifty Years Ago, Last Outpost of Segregation in N.F.L. Fell|date=October 6, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/07/sports/football/50-years-ago-redskins-were-last-nfl-team-to-integrate.html|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> [[Bill McPeak]], in his first year as head coach, immediately announced Mitchell would become a [[Wide receiver#Types|flanker]].  In his first game in Washington, Mitchell ran back a 92-yard kickoff return against the [[Dallas Cowboys]].<ref name=hofbiography />  The Redskins finished the season with a 5\u20137\u20132 record, their best record in five years.<ref name=basen_10062012/> Mitchell led the league with 72 catches and 1384 yards and ranked third with 11 touchdowns.<ref name=hofbiography/><ref name=basen_10062012/> He was selected to the first of three consecutive Pro Bowls.<ref name=washpost_obit/>\n\nIn [[1963 NFL season|1963]], Mitchell recorded 69 catches for 1436 yards and seven more touchdowns. During this season, he also became the second player in league and franchise history to record a [[99-yard pass play]]. The pass from [[George Izo]] was the first 99-yard pass in over 23 years, when the Redskins' [[Frank Filchock]] and [[Andy Farkas]] set the original record October 15, 1939.<ref name=hofbiography />  During the next four years, Mitchell's reception totals were 60, 60, 58 and 60.<ref name=hofbiography />  In [[1967 NFL season|1967]], new head coach [[Otto Graham]] chose to move Mitchell back to [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] because of Graham's decision a year earlier to move the team's best running back, [[Charley Taylor]], to wide receiver.  Mitchell enjoyed only moderate success running the ball but he did catch 60 passes for 866 yards and six touchdowns.<ref name=hofbiography />\n\nIn [[1969 NFL season|1969]], [[Vince Lombardi]] became head coach and promised Mitchell that he would return him to flanker.<ref name=hofbiography />  But as [[National Football League Training Camp|training camp]] progressed, Mitchell realized that he was not in the same shape he once was and chose to retire.<ref name=hofbiography />\n\nDuring his first six seasons with the Redskins, Mitchell never caught fewer than 58 passes.<ref name=hofprofile />  When he retired, his 14,078 combined net yards was the second highest total in NFL history.<ref name=hofprofile />  He had also scored 91 touchdowns (18 by rushing, 65 on receptions, 3 on punt returns, and 5 on kickoff returns).  He amassed 7,954 yards on receptions and 2,735 yards on rushes.<ref name=hofprofile />  He was elected to the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] in 1983.<ref name=hofbiography/>\n\n==Front-office career (1969\u20132003)==\nAfter retiring from football in 1968, Mitchell remained with the Redskins, at the request of then [[head coach]] [[Vince Lombardi]], as a pro [[Scout (sport)|scout]].<ref name=frontoffice>{{cite web | work=St. Petersburg Times | url=http://www.sptimes.com/2003/02/01/Sports/Mitchell_leaves_Redsk.shtml | title=Mitchell leaves Redskins | accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref> He gradually moved up in the ranks to assistant [[general manager]] in the organization,<ref name=integrate/> and he aspired to become the NFL's first black GM.<ref name=frontoffice /> In 1978, Washington owner [[Edward Bennett Williams]] passed over Mitchell for the GM position in favor of [[Bobby Beathard]].<ref name=washpost_obit/><ref name=frontoffice /> Mitchell retired in 2003, stating that he was \"deeply hurt\" by how owner [[Jack Kent Cooke]] passed him over as the team's general manager in favor of [[Charley Casserly]] in 1998 and by coach [[Steve Spurrier]]'s decision to issue his No. 49 uniform number, which had not been issued for years though never [[retired number|retired]], to [[Leonard Stephens]] that season.<ref name=washpost_obit/><ref name=frontoffice />\n\nAs a player and a front office executive, Mitchell spent 41 years with the Redskins.<ref name=frontoffice />\n\n==Personal life==\nMitchell lived in [[Washington D.C.]] with his wife, Gwen who is an attorney. They had two children, Robert, Jr and Terri.<ref name=illini />\n\nBeginning in 1980, Mitchell hosted the Bobby Mitchell Hall of Fame Classic, an annual golf fundraiser that benefits the [[Leukemia & Lymphoma Society]].<ref>{{cite news | work=Washington Post | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/12/AR2005071201798_pf.html | title='Happy Because He Has Hope' | accessdate=June 27, 2008 | first=Walter | last=Gabriel}}</ref>\n\nMitchell also worked in many efforts and organizations, including the [[United Negro College Fund]], the [[Howard University]] Cancer Research Advisory Committee, the [[American Lung Association]] of D.C., the [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Day|Martin Luther King Jr. Holiday Commission]], the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys Club of Washington]], the [[National Urban League]], the [[NAACP]], the [[Junior Chamber of Commerce]], the University of Illinois Presidents Council and the University of Illinois Foundation.<ref name=illini />\n\nMitchell died at age 84 on April 5, 2020.<ref name=goldstein_04052020>{{cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Richard|title=Bobby Mitchell, Hall of Famer and the Redskins\u2019 First Black Star, Dies at 84|date=April 5, 2020|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/05/sports/football/bobby-mitchell-dead.html|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Profootballhof|152|Bobby Mitchell}}\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=MIT650992 |cfl= |afl= |espn= |cbs= |yahoo= |fox= |si= |pfr=M/MitcBo00 |rotoworld=}}\n{{Browns1958DraftPicks}}\n{{NFL receiving touchdown leaders}}\n{{NFL receiving yardage leaders}}\n{{The 70 Greatest Redskins}}\n{{Washington Redskins Ring of Fame}}\n{{Washington Redskins}}\n{{1983 Football HOF}}\n{{Pro Football Hall of Fame members}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football halfbacks]]\n[[Category:American football return specialists]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n[[Category:Illinois Fighting Illini football players]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins executives]]\n[[Category:Washington Redskins players]]\n[[Category:Eastern Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Pro Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Hot Springs High School (Arkansas) alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hot Springs, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Arkansas]]\n", "name_user": "Bagumba", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCleveland Browns (1958\u20131961):ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobby_Mitchell"}
